text: A Dense Fog Advisory will remain in effect for much of the area through 7 AM Friday. Henrietta, N.Y. – A Rochester woman faces charges after police say they found her unconscious behind the wheel at an intersection. Police responded to reports of a suspicious vehicle at the intersection of Jefferson Road and Jay Scutti Boulevard in Henrietta around 4:40 a.m. on Christmas Eve. After running the license plates, officers discovered the car had been reported stolen two weeks ago. Police say the driver, Casey R. Clohessy, 36, was unconscious behind the wheel of a Nissan Sentra with drug paraphernalia visible. After deputies attempted to put the car in park, Clohessy allegedly woke up and tried to drive off. A deputy removed the keys from the ignition. Police said Clohessy tried to run away but was taken into custody. Clohessy is charged criminal possession of stolen property, operating a motor vehicle while under the influence of alcohol or drugs, aggravated unlicensed operation and resisting arrest. She also had outstanding warrants out of Monroe County Court, Rochester City Court and Irondequoit Town Court. She faces an additional charge of criminal possession of stolen property stemming from a warrant. Clohessy was arraigned in Henrietta Town Court and taken to Monroe County Jail on a warrant. She remains listed on the jail roster.

title: Cold Wave: No ‘cold day’ as Delhi logs warmest December in 6 years | Delhi News - Times of India
text: NEW DELHI: In December this year, the mean maximum temperature was 24.1 degrees Celsius, significantly higher than the normal of 22.8 degrees C, while the mean minimum was 8.6 degrees C, a shade higher than the normal (8.4 degrees C). Not since 2017 have both the mean maximum and minimum temperatures been above normal in December.On the last day of the year, however, the day temperature dipped to the season’s lowest of 15.9 degrees Celsius at Safdarjung on Sunday, 4.5 degrees below normal. However, the met department said while the maximum temperature met conditions for a ‘cold day’ to the declared, the minimum temperature did not. The day’s minimum was 11.7 degrees C while for ‘cold day’ conditions to be met, it has to be below 10 degrees. In the city, SPS Mayur Vihar saw the lowest maximum temperature of 13.3 degrees C. 106426424Officials said cold day conditions are likely at isolated places on Monday with ‘yellow’ alert in place. December 2023 just ‘trace’ rainfall on one day and ended with a rain deficit of 100%. Kuldeep Srivastava, scientist and head, Regional Weather Forecasting Centre, IMD, said, “The western disturbances, which impacted the hills, were not strong enough to cause significant snowfall in western Himalayan region. Only light snowfall was recorded in December and the snow melted easily. Whenever there is a good snowfall, the north-westerly winds bring chilly winds to Delhi.”The plains saw two feeble western disturbances in December. “In absence of a strong western disturbance impacting the plains, only drizzles were recorded at isolated places in Delhi. Since there was no cloudiness, the sun shone brightly on most days leading to a higher day temperature than normal. As winds blew on most days, the minimum temperature also did not witness a sharp dip,” said Srivastava. 106333509The average maximum temperature in December was two degrees higher than the normal mark. Safdarjung, the city’s base station, recorded day temperature in the range of 24-25 degrees Celsius on most days and the maximum temperature saw a drop only in the last week of December. The day temperature was below 20 degrees Celsius on two days- December 30 and 31. 106392411Like at Safdarjung, the difference in maximum and minimum temperatures at other stations on Sunday was low. The maximum and minimum temperatures were 16.1 and 11.7 degrees Celsius at Palam, 15 and 10.8 degrees Celsius at Lodhi Road and 15 and 12.1 degrees Celsius at Jafarpur, respectively.“Throughout the day, Delhi saw uplifted fog. As the fog was at surface height of 100-150 metres, it looked like clouds,” said Srivastava. The maximum and minimum temperatures are likely to be around 16 and 8 degrees Celsius on Monday. 106281981

author: MRT Desk
title: Leah Remini and Angelo Pagan to Divorce After 21 Years of Marriage
text:
Leah Remini, renowned for her roles in Kevin Can Wait , King of Queens , and Saved By the Bell , has announced that she and her husband, Angelo Pagan, will be divorcing after 21 years of marriage. Their relationship spans 28 years, making this change significant for both parties.
Leah Remini and Angelo Pagan have declared their intention to divorce. File Photo by Jim Ruymen/UPI On Instagram, the couple shared their decision with the world. ‘We have decided to file for divorce,’ they wrote, indicating a mutual understanding of the situation.
The couple at the Primetime Emmy Awards in Los Angeles in 2006. File Photo by Jim Ruymen/UPI In their heartfelt message, they expressed, ‘This decision came after a lot of thought and care.’ They acknowledged the difficulty of divorce but emphasized their positive outlook. ‘We know it’s what’s best for us,’ they stated. Their commitment to handling the situation amicably is evident in their words.
The couple also reflected on their shared journey, admitting, ‘We are proud of how we have worked through this together.’ They conveyed their sadness about the split but reassured their followers that they would continue to support each other. ‘We’ve got some figuring out to do as we continue to move forward into our new normal—together still in many ways, and apart in some new ones,’ they added.
Leah Remini at the world premiere of Second Act in New York City in 2018. File Photo by John Angelillo/UPI Together, Leah Remini and Angelo Pagan share a daughter named Sofia, who is 20 years old. Pagán also has three sons—Angelo Jr., Alex, and Nico—from a previous relationship, further expanding their family dynamics.
Leah Remini at the Creative Arts Emmy Awards in 2018. File Photo by Gregg DeGuire/UPI Leah Remini at the “Funny Ladies We Love” awards presented by Ladies’ Home Journal in 2006 in Los Angeles. File Photo by Michael Tweed/UPI The public is often drawn to celebrity relationships, especially those that span decades. Remini and Pagan’s commitment to approach this transition positively is encouraging amid the challenges that come with such a significant life change. Like many couples, they have faced ups and downs, but their dedication to maintaining a supportive relationship for their daughter and blended family remains commendable.
As they embark on their new journey separately, fans and well-wishers alike are hopeful for happiness and fulfillment for both Leah Remini and Angelo Pagan in the next chapters of their lives.
Source: UPI

author: Matt Margolis
title: Joe Biden Gets a Participation Trophy From the Media for This? – PJ Media
text:
The media sure is desperate to find something to boast about from Joe Biden's campaign. Anyone who has been paying attention recently knows, there isn't a lot of good news from the Biden camp these days. Even after the verdict from Donald Trump's sham trial in New York, Biden couldn't manage to take a solid lead in the polls. So now, they're taking something embarrassing and passing it off as a huge victory for Biden.
I'm not exaggerating. Politico has written a puff piece about Joe Biden having his "biggest online fundraising day" after Trump's conviction.
"Donald Trump wasn’t the only one to get a fundraising boost off his New York hush money conviction — so did Joe Biden," the outlet writes . "The president’s campaign had its single biggest day of online fundraising the day after Trump was convicted, according to a POLITICO analysis of federal campaign finance data. And as the money flowed in, his political operation also drew more new donors the day of the verdict than any day since Biden launched his campaign last year."
It sounds like Biden achieved something amazing, doesn't it? He must have been going all Scrooge McDuck, just diving into piles and piles of money, right? It sure sounds like it, based on the way they're hyping this up. The article didn't give a number just yet, so Politico had to keep hyping it up.
Related : Have You Seen the Newest Trump Ads? Stop What You're Doing and Check Them Out!
According to the report, on the day of the verdict and the day after, the Biden campaign "brought in totals six times higher than Biden’s typical fundraising day."
The suspense is killing you, isn't it?
" The boost for the incumbent, and a smaller one for down-ballot Democrats, made the day after Trump’s conviction the biggest overall fundraising day on ActBlue so far this cycle," the article continues.
Finally, five paragraphs into the story, Politico reveals Joe Biden's big fundraiser boon: $8.1 million.
Yep. That's it. That's $8.1 million between the Biden campaign and two joint fundraising committees.
Let's put that in perspective: The Trump campaign and its joint fundraising committees raised $52.8 million in the first 24 hours after the verdict , more than $2 million an hour.
Related: The Biden Campaign Must Be Freaking Out Over This News
Politico didn't even try to pretend that Biden's haul was impressive compared to Trump's. The article conceded that Biden's $8.1 million take "still pales in comparison to what Trump’s campaign said it raised in the aftermath of his conviction. The former president’s massive intake of donations helped him overtake Biden in cash on hand."
Now you understand why Politico buried the lede. Yet the outlet still tried to put lipstick on the pig.
The article said the "surge in financial support for Biden suggests the conviction was a wake-up call for many grassroots donors who have been holding back so far this cycle, and it’s a much-needed moment of fundraising energy for Biden’s campaign."
Isn't that cute? Donald Trump eclipses Joe Biden's fundraising and erases his cash advantage in a flash, yet, according to Politico, it's the Biden campaign that has awoken the sleeping giant. It's like Politico awarded Biden a participation trophy for his fundraising and thought we wouldn't notice.
